04755nam a22006015i 9780822393023DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223930237 a10.1515/97808223930232doi  a(DE-B1597)554020  a(OCoLC)662618964  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS778.M3 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a951.050921 aKarl, Rebecca E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMao Zedong and China in the Twentieth-Century World :bA Concise History /cRebecca E. Karl; ed. by Michael Dutton, Rey Chow, Harry Harootunian, Rosalind C. Morris. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (214 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society : 4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- t1. China in the World in Mao’s Youth -- t2. From Liberal to Communist, 1912–1921 -- t3. Toward the Peasant Revolution, 1921–1927 -- t4. Establishing Revolutionary Bases -- t5. Yan’an, the War of Resistance against Japan, and Civil War, 1935–1949 -- t6. Stabilizing Society and the Transition to Socialism, 1949–1957 -- t7. Great Leap and Restoration, 1958–1965 -- t8. The Cultural Revolution -- t9. The Cultural Revolution -- t10. Reform, Restoration, and the Repudiation of Maoism, 1976–Present -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout this lively and concise historical account of Mao Zedong’s life and thought, Rebecca E. Karl places the revolutionary leader’s personal experiences, social visions and theory, military strategies, and developmental and foreign policies in a dynamic narrative of the Chinese revolution. She situates Mao and the revolution in a global setting informed by imperialism, decolonization, and third worldism, and discusses worldwide trends in politics, the economy, military power, and territorial sovereignty. Karl begins with Mao’s early life in a small village in Hunan province, documenting his relationships with his parents, passion for education, and political awakening during the fall of the Qing dynasty in late 1911. She traces his transition from liberal to Communist over the course of the next decade, his early critiques of the subjugation of women, and the gathering force of the May 4th movement for reform and radical change. Describing Mao’s rise to power, she delves into the dynamics of Communist organizing in an overwhelmingly agrarian society, and Mao’s confrontations with Chiang Kaishek and other nationalist conservatives. She also considers his marriages and romantic liaisons and their relation to Mao as the revolutionary founder of Communism in China. After analyzing Mao’s stormy tenure as chairman of the People’s Republic of China, Karl concludes by examining his legacy in China from his death in 1976 through the Beijing Olympics in 2008.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHeads of statezChinavBiography. 0aHeads of statezChinaxBiography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aChow, Rey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDutton, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarootunian, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorris, Rosalind C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393023zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393023423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822393023/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  